[[Category:Physical exercise]]

:''For a type of guide for 18th and 19th century travellers see [[Bear-leader (guide)]].'' [[File:Dr James Hay as Bear Leader, 1704-1729.png|thumb|right|A caricature of a bear-leader]] A '''bear-leader''' was formerly a man who led [[bear]]s about the country. In the [[Middle Ages]] and the [[Tudor period]], these animals were chiefly used in the [[blood sport]] of [[bear-baiting]] and were led from village to village. Performing bears were also common; their keepers were generally [[French people|Frenchmen]] or [[Italian people|Italians]].<ref name="EB1911">{{EB1911|inline=1|wstitle=Bear-Leader|volume=3|page=582}}</ref>
Later, the phrase "bear-leader" came colloquially to mean a [[tutor]] or [[Legal guardian|guardian]], who escorted any young man of rank or wealth on his travels.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}
