{{for|the song by Swedish rock band [[Razorlight]]|Wire to Wire (song)}}
{{Underlinked|date=September 2016}}
'''Wire-to-wire''' is a term used in competitive events and sports for a champion who maintained the lead during an entire competition. The term is most commonly associated with [[golf]] referencing a player who wins a title while holding the lowest aggregate score at the close of each round.<ref name="pga._Dann">{{Cite web |title=Danny Willett wins Masters after Jordan Spieth's shocking stumble |first=Doug |last=Ferguson |publisher=PGA of America |date=April 10, 2016 |access-date=April 12, 2016 |url=http://www.pga.com/news/masters/danny-willett-wins-masters-after-shocking-stumble-jordan-spieth}}</ref><ref name="golf_Dayc">{{Cite news |title=Day closes out wire-to-wire victory at Bay Hill |first=Doug |last=Ferguson |work=Golf Channel |date=March 20, 2016 |access-date=April 12, 2016 |url=http://www.golfchannel.com/news/doug-ferguson/day-closes-out-wire-wire-victory-bay-hill/}}</ref><ref name="stan_Wome">{{Cite news |title=Women’s golf leads from wire to wire in dominant Silverado Showdown showing |first=Do-Hyoung |last=Park |work=Stanford Daily |date=April 6, 2016 |access-date=April 12, 2016 |url=http://www.stanforddaily.com/2016/04/06/womens-golf-leads-from-wire-to-wire-in-dominant-silverado-showdown-showing/}}</ref>  It is also a commonly used term in horse racing, to denote a horse that leads a race from start to finish.

